## Meta - OS:   Linux  Selenium Version:   2.53.1  Browser:   Firefox  Browser Version:   Mozilla Firefox 46.0.1  ## Expected Behavior - What I *expect* is that the documentation here:  https://seleniumhq.github.io/selenium/docs/api/java/org/openqa/selenium/JavascriptExecutor.html#executeScript-java.lang.String-java.lang.Object...-  States that when you are returning a javscript object in a script, like so: ```         JavascriptExecutor jsExecutor = (JavascriptExecutor) browser.getWebDriver();         Map performanceInformation = (Map) jsExecutor.executeScript("return window.performance"); ```  You receive a Map back, that  represents the java object. (Note that the documentation does not state that, see Actual behavior below)  Like so: (the below output was created by running Gson on the object to turn the string into a pretty-printed object)  ``` {   "getEntriesByName": "function getEntriesByName() {
    [native code]
}",   "setResourceTimingBufferSize": "function setResourceTimingBufferSize() {
    [native code]
}",   "clearMeasures": "function clearMeasures() {
    [native code]
}",   "timing": {     "unloadEventEnd": 0,     "responseEnd": 1488588634624,     "responseStart": 1488588634590,     "unloadEventStart": 0,     "domainLookupEnd": 1488588634244,     "domInteractive": 1488588706002,     "domContentLoadedEventStart": 1488588706003,     "domComplete": 1488588706011,     "domainLookupStart": 1488588634244,     "redirectEnd": 0,     "redirectStart": 0,     "toJSON": "function toJSON() {
    [native code]
}",     "connectEnd": 1488588634244,     "connectStart": 1488588634244,     "loadEventStart": 1488588706011,     "navigationStart": 1488588634242,     "requestStart": 1488588634253,     "fetchStart": 1488588634244,     "domContentLoadedEventEnd": 1488588706010,     "domLoading": 1488588634595,     "loadEventEnd": 1488588706011   },   "getEntriesByType": "function getEntriesByType() {
    [native code]
}",   "toJSON": "function toJSON() {
    [native code]
}",   "navigation": {     "redirectCount": 0,     "TYPE_RESERVED": 255,     "toJSON": "function toJSON() {
    [native code]
}",     "TYPE_NAVIGATE": 0,     "TYPE_RELOAD": 1,     "type": 0,     "TYPE_BACK_FORWARD": 2   },   "measure": "function measure() {
    [native code]
}",   "getEntries": "function getEntries() {
    [native code]
}",   "clearMarks": "function clearMarks() {
    [native code]
}",   "now": "function now() {
    [native code]
}",   "clearResourceTimings": "function clearResourceTimings() {
    [native code]
}",   "mark": "function mark() {
    [native code]
}" } ``` ## Actual Behavior -  The documentation states:  " If the script has a return value (i.e. if the script contains a return statement), then the following steps will be taken:      For an HTML element, this method returns a WebElement     For a decimal, a Double is returned     For a non-decimal number, a Long is returned     For a boolean, a Boolean is returned     For all other cases, a String is returned.     For an array, return a List with each object following the rules above. We support nested lists.     Unless the value is null or there is no return value, in which null is returned "  Which clearly indicates that if you return a javascript object, you will be in the "all other cases" case, and receive a string.  I'm happy with what the code does (a map representing the javascript object), but the documentation is misleading, and leads to one casting the return to a string, and having to sort out errors like:  ``` java.util.concurrent.ExecutionException: java.lang.ClassCastException: com.google.common.collect.Maps$TransformedEntriesMap cannot be cast to java.lang.String         at java.util.concurrent.FutureTask.report(FutureTask.java:122)         at java.util.concurrent.FutureTask.get(FutureTask.java:206)        [removed for privacy]  Caused by: java.lang.ClassCastException: com.google.common.collect.Maps$TransformedEntriesMap cannot be cast to java.lang.String         [removed for privacy]         at java.util.concurrent.FutureTask.run(FutureTask.java:266)         at java.util.concurrent.ThreadPoolExecutor.runWorker(ThreadPoolExecutor.java:1142)         at java.util.concurrent.ThreadPoolExecutor$Worker.run(ThreadPoolExecutor.java:617)         at java.lang.Thread.run(Thread.java:745) ```  ## Steps to reproduce - - read the docs on executeScript - code up your program following the documented steps, casting a return object to a string. - BOOM!

